# Feature Spec Quality Standards

When editing or reviewing feature specs, enforce these quality criteria.

## Required Structure

Every spec MUST include:

1. **YAML frontmatter** with all required fields (id, code, title, area, keywords, platforms, risk, status, app_version)
2. **Summary**: 2-3 sentence plain-language description
3. **Scenarios**: At least one scenario in structured format
4. **Changelog**: Version history table

Optional sections (include when applicable):
- **Requirements**: RFC 2119 constraints (performance, reliability, security)
- **Edge Cases**: Boundary conditions and error states
- **Platform Differences**: Where desktop/iOS/Android diverge
- **Regression Notes**: Historical fragility and tribal knowledge

## Scenario Quality Checks

Every scenario MUST have all five fields:
- **Priority**: One of Critical, High, Medium, Low
- **Platforms**: Specific platforms (Desktop, iOS, Android) — not "all"
- **Preconditions**: Explicit list — never assume context
- **Action**: Describes user intent, NOT specific UI interactions (no "click button X", "tap field Y")
- **Expected**: Concrete, verifiable outcomes with clear pass/fail criteria

## Requirement Language (RFC 2119)

Use uppercase RFC 2119 keywords for requirement strength:
- **SHALL** / **MUST**: Absolute requirement — failure is a defect
- **SHALL NOT** / **MUST NOT**: Absolute prohibition
- **SHOULD**: Recommended but deviations are acceptable with justification
- **MAY**: Optional

Never use lowercase "should", "must", "needs to" in requirements. These are ambiguous.

## Flag These Vague Terms

| Vague Term | Replace With |
|------------|-------------|
| "fast" | "< X seconds" (specify threshold) |
| "smooth" | "> X FPS" or "< X ms latency" |
| "secure" | Specific security property (encrypted at rest, etc.) |
| "user-friendly" | Specific usability criterion |
| "reliable" | Specific failure rate or recovery behaviour |
| "seamless" | Specific user flow without interruption |
| "properly" / "correctly" | Specific expected behaviour or output |
| "responsive" | "< X ms" or "adapts to viewport width" |
| "works" | Specific observable outcome |
| "displays properly" | Specific visual state or content |

## ID Rules

- Scenario IDs: `SC-{CODE}-{NUM}` (e.g., SC-CHAN-01)
- Edge case IDs: `EC-{CODE}-{NUM}` (e.g., EC-CHAN-01)
- `{CODE}` MUST match the spec's `code` frontmatter field
- IDs are permanent — NEVER renumber
- Deleted IDs are NEVER reused
- New scenarios always get the next available number

## Frontmatter Validation

Required fields and accepted values:

```yaml
id: string          # kebab-case, unique across all specs
code: string        # UPPERCASE, 2-5 chars, unique across all specs
title: string       # Human-readable feature name
area: string        # One of: communities, wallet, messaging, onboarding, settings
keywords: [string]  # Domain terms for search and bug matching
platforms: [string]  # Subset of: desktop, ios, android
risk: string        # One of: low, medium, high, critical
status: string      # One of: draft, active, deprecated
app_version: string # Semver or release number this spec reflects
```

Optional fields:
```yaml
refs:
  epic: string      # GitHub issue URL
  figma: string     # Figma design URL
automation:
  desktop: string   # Path to desktop test directory in status-app
  mobile: string    # Path to mobile test directory in status-app
```

## Cross-Reference Rules

- Link to other specs using relative paths: `[Community Permissions](community-permissions.md)`
- Link to FURPS docs using full GitHub URLs: `[Communities FURPS](https://github.com/status-im/status-app/blob/develop/docs/FURPS/communities.md)`
- Link to test code using repository-relative paths: `test/e2e/tests/communities/`
- Reference scenario IDs in plain text: "See SC-PERM-03 for permission validation"
